additive identity formula_53 and multiplicative identity formula_54

The function 
:formula_55
defines a ring homomorphism from formula_56 into formula_9 which is injective if and only if does not contain any zero divisors.

If formula_58 then formula_4 is the zero ring that has as unique element.

If is the set of all regular elements of (that is the elements that are not zero divisors), formula_4 is called the total ring of fractions of .

=== Universal property ===
The (above defined) ring homomorphism formula_61 satisfies a universal property that is described below. This characterizes formula_4 up to an isomorphism. So all properties of localizations can be deduced from the universal property, independently from the way they have been constructed. Moreover, many important properties of localization are easily deduced from the general properties of universal properties, while their direct proof may be more technical.

The universal property satisfied by formula_61 is the following: 
:If formula_64 is a ring homomorphism that maps every element of to a unit (invertible element) in , there exists a unique ring homomorphism formula_65 such that formula_66

Using category theory, this can be expressed by saying that localization is a functor that is left adjoint to a forgetful functor. More precisely, let formula_67 and formula_68 be the categories whose objects are pairs of a commutative ring and a submonoid of, respectively, the multiplicative monoid or the group of units of the ring. The morphisms of these categories are the ring homomorphisms that map the submonoid of the first object into the submonoid of the second one. Finally, let formula_69 be the forgetful functor that forgets that the elements of the second element of the pair are invertible.

Then the factorization formula_70 of the universal property defines a bijection
:formula_71

This may seem a rather tricky way of expressing the universal property, but it is useful for showing easily many properties, by using the fact that the composition of two left adjoint functors is a left adjoint functor.

