<doc id="252235" wikidata="Q840023" url="?curid=252235" title="Nilpotent">
<text>In mathematics, an element formula_1 of a ring formula_2 is called nilpotent if there exists some positive integer formula_3, called the index (or sometimes the degree), such that formula_4.

The term, along with its sister idempotent, was introduced by Benjamin Peirce in the context of his work on the classification of algebras.

== Examples ==

*This definition can be applied in particular to square matrices. The matrix
:: formula_5
:is nilpotent because formula_6. See nilpotent matrix for more.

* In the factor ring formula_7, the equivalence class of 3 is nilpotent because 32 is congruent to 0 modulo 9.
* Assume that two elements formula_8 and formula_9 in a ring formula_2 satisfy formula_11. Then the element formula_12 is nilpotent as formula_13 An example with matrices (for &quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;):formula_14 Here formula_15 and formula_16.

*By definition, any element of a nilsemigroup is nilpotent.

== Properties ==
No nilpotent element can be a unit (except in the trivial ring, which has only a single element ). All nilpotent elements are zero divisors.

An formula_17 matrix formula_18 with entries from a field is nilpotent if and only if its characteristic polynomial is formula_19.

If formula_1 is nilpotent, then formula_21 is a unit, because formula_4 entails formula_23

More generally, the sum of a unit element and a nilpotent element is a unit when they commute.

== Commutative rings ==
The nilpotent elements from a commutative ring formula_2 form an ideal formula_25; this is a consequence of the binomial theorem. This ideal is the nilradical of the ring. Every nilpotent element formula_1 in a commutative ring is contained in every prime ideal formula_27 of that ring, since formula_28. So formula_25 is contained in the intersection of all prime ideals.

If formula_1 is not nilpotent, we are able to localize with respect to the powers of formula_1: formula_32 to get a non-zero ring formula_33. The prime ideals of the localized ring correspond exactly to those prime ideals formula_27 of formula_2 with formula_36. As every non-zero commutative ring has a maximal ideal, which is prime, every non-nilpotent formula_1 is not contained in some prime ideal. Thus formula_25 is exactly the intersection of all prime ideals.

A characteristic similar to that of Jacobson radical and annihilation of simple modules is available for nilradical: nilpotent elements of a ring formula_2 are precisely those that annihilate all integral domains internal to the ring formula_2 (that is, of the form formula_41 for prime ideals formula_42). This follows from the fact that nilradical is the intersection of all prime ideals.

== Nilpotent elements in Lie algebra ==
Let formula_43 be a Lie algebra. Then an element formula_44 is called nilpotent if it is in formula_45 and formula_46 is a nilpotent transformation. See also: Jordan decomposition in a Lie algebra.

==Nilpotency in physics==

Any ladder operator in a finite dimensional space is nilpotent. They represent creation and annihilation operators, which transform from one state to another, for example the raising and lowering Pauli matrices formula_47. 

An operand formula_48 that satisfies formula_49 is nilpotent. Grassmann numbers which allow a path integral representation for Fermionic fields are nilpotents since their squares vanish. The BRST charge is an important example in physics.

As linear operators form an associative algebra and thus a ring, this is a special case of the initial definition. More generally, in view of the above definitions, an operator formula_48 is nilpotent if there is formula_51 such that formula_52 (the zero function). Thus, a linear map is nilpotent iff it has a nilpotent matrix in some basis. Another example for this is the exterior derivative (again with formula_53). Both are linked, also through supersymmetry and Morse theory, as shown by Edward Witten in a celebrated article.

The electromagnetic field of a plane wave without sources is nilpotent when it is expressed in terms of the algebra of physical space. More generally, the technique of microadditivity (which can used to derive theorems in physics) makes use of nilpotent or nilsquare infinitesimals and is part smooth infinitesimal analysis.

==Algebraic nilpotents==
The two-dimensional dual numbers contain a nilpotent space. Other algebras and numbers that contain nilpotent spaces include split-quaternions (coquaternions), split-octonions,
biquaternions formula_54, and complex octonions formula_55. If a nilpotent infinitesimal is a variable tending to zero, it can be shown that any sum of terms for which it is the subject is an indefinitely small proportion of the first order term.

==See also==
*Idempotent element (ring theory)
*Unipotent
*Reduced ring
*Nil ideal
*Nilpotent matrix

